xenoCantoData.file-name: XC696692-STAR, 4 Phasen u. Motiv  18.3.2012  HhSpPl  8_11_10 - 8_14_22   LS101903  f. CD2.mp3
xenoCantoData.rmk:
Starlings sing in their breeding area around their nisting boxes. One of them  sings 4 phrases:
artspecific whistle at the beginning, then a long second phase (until 00:30) with a mix of individuel whistles, rattling (Rätschen"), blathering ("Schwätzen") etc.,  and a lot of imitations: in 00:07 Vanellus vanellus, in 00:16 alarm call of Erithacus rubecula and so on.  Phase 3: shorter and lower with cracking (knackenden) and chattering (ratternden) sounds. Phase 4: shrill screeching (Kreischen) with wings flattering.  From  00:46 in the foreground  a Starling, which prefers  a very special rhythm motive, only song in this summer period. I am always fascinated of the artspecfic and different individual whistlings of  Starlings! Same Starlings and situation as in XC696691

Another often repeats a three- or foursyllabic motive - may be the modificied song of Poecile montana (first in 00:09). In 01:57 imitation of Falco tinninculus, in  03:14 of Buteo buteo etc. etc .
